<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?><listPerson xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><person xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="BEL01" sex="1"><persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><roleName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/><forename xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Thomas</forename><surname xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Belsham</surname><addName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/></persName><birth xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1750-04-15"><placeName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/></birth><death xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1829-11-11"/><occupation xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Unitarian minister</occupation><note xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="editorial"><p xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Belsham was professor of divinity at New College, Hackney 1789-1796. He later succeeded <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="DIS01">John Disney</persName> at the 
      Essex Street Chapel, the foremost 
    dissenting chapel in London, in 1805. He was persistently engaged with the struggle for civil rights for dissenters. </p><p xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">It is possible that the references are to his brother <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="BEL02">William</persName> who also moved in reforming circles. However, as Godwin 
      distinguishes W Belsham in the 1796 list and notes the encounter in 1805 which matches the '2 Belshams' of 18 June that year, it is reasonable to assume that 
      Godwin's main contact was with Thomas.</p><p xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"> There are seven entries to Belcham in the 1780s and early 1790s.  These are in circles with the Hollis's, Kippis, Price, and others strongly linked to dissent. 
  It is unusual for Godwin to mispell names - and to use different spellings interchangeably (although see Hays/Hayes), although in this case there is only one Belsham before the Belcham's stop. .  Nonetheless there is at least presumptive 
  evidence for these entries being references to Thomas Belsham. The entries are on 25  September  1789; 3  November  1789; 4  November  1789; 1  February  1790;
  5  March  1790; 30  November  1790; and 11  January  1791.  They have been coded for Thomas Belsham, in large part because of the almost identical pattern of the 
  circles in which the names appear, although there must remain some doubt over the attribution.
